#!/bin/bash
echo $((2#$BINARY))
Explanation:
First line: #!/bin/bash - Shebang specifying Bash interpreter

Second line: echo $((2#$BINARY)) - Uses arithmetic expansion with base conversion

How it works:
2#$BINARY uses the base conversion syntax covered in Package 2: [base#]n

2# specifies that the following number is in base 2 (binary)

$BINARY undergoes parameter expansion to get the binary string

The arithmetic expansion $((2#$BINARY)) converts the binary number to decimal

echo prints the decimal result followed by a newline

Demonstration:
bash
julien@production-503e7013:~/$ export BINARY=10100111001
julien@production-503e7013:~/$ ./11-binary_to_decimal
1337
Calculation:
Binary 10100111001 = Decimal 1337

1×1024 + 0×512 + 1×256 + 0×128 + 0×64 + 1×32 + 1×16 + 1×8 + 0×4 + 0×2 + 1×1 = 1337

Key concepts demonstrated:
Arithmetic expansion with $(())

Base conversion syntax - [base#]n (covered in Package 2)

Binary to decimal conversion using 2#binary_number

Parameter expansion with environment variables

This script will work in your sandbox environment and correctly convert any binary number stored in the BINARY environment variable to its decimal equivalent.

